{#- TL;DR (body) — canonical figures verbatim. #pcfo-tldr-body = speakable. -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="pcfo-tldr">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">In one paragraph</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:16px;">What a fractional CFO costs.</h2>
    <div class="tldr-prose"><p id="pcfo-tldr-body">A fractional CFO at TechBrot is a <strong>monthly retainer of $3,000&ndash;$8,000+</strong>, accepted <strong>by application</strong> with limited capacity each quarter. Unlike bookkeeping &mdash; which is priced on transaction volume and the size of the close &mdash; the CFO retainer is priced on <strong>judgment and depth of involvement</strong>: how often you need strategic finance in the room, how many entities sit under you, whether there&rsquo;s a fundraise, board, or lender in play, and the cadence of the reporting and forecasting you need. The retainer is fixed, not hourly, and scoped per engagement after a free discovery call &mdash; the exact number in writing before you commit. This is advisory work: it is <strong>not tax filing and not audit or assurance</strong>, and it coordinates with your CPA rather than replacing one. Acceptance isn&rsquo;t guaranteed; senior engagements are limited.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

{#- DIFFERENT — prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="pcfo-different" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Why it isn&rsquo;t priced like bookkeeping</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:14px;">Judgment, not transaction volume.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Bookkeeping pricing is volume math. Count the transactions, the bank and credit accounts, the entities, the payroll runs &mdash; the fee tracks the size of the monthly close. The work is largely the same shape every month, so it prices cleanly as a recurring fixed fee.</p>
      <p>A fractional CFO is the opposite. The deliverable isn&rsquo;t a reconciled ledger &mdash; it&rsquo;s <strong>decisions you can defend</strong>: a forecast a lender will trust, a board package that survives questions, a pricing or hiring call backed by unit economics, a cash runway you can act on before it&rsquo;s a crisis. None of that scales with transaction count. A 30-transaction-a-month startup raising a seed round can need more CFO time than a 2,000-transaction business that just wants someone steering the quarter.</p>
      <p>So the retainer is priced on the <strong>depth of involvement the business actually needs</strong>, not on how busy the books are. That&rsquo;s also why it&rsquo;s accepted by application: senior strategic capacity is finite, and the engagement only works when the scope is honest on both sides.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

